<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / Sheffield censured over student games
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government's watchdog on public spending has severely criticised
Sheffield City Council for failing to monitor and manage last year's World
Student Games, held in the city. The games unexpectedly lost Pounds 10.4m
after the council had budgeted Pounds 5m of public funds to cover a
shortfall of income.
Mr Gordon Sutton, the district auditor responsible for monitoring the
council's spending, says those running the games failed to install proper
systems of financial control and had no idea of the scale of impending
losses only weeks before the games took place in July.
The games failed to achieve expected revenue from television rights,
commercial sponsorship, merchandising and ticket sales. Sharp cutting of
costs as the shortfall became apparent led to some loss of control. One
economy measure - to cut resources in the box office - resulted in it
becoming impossible to reconcile ticket sales with cash receipts.
The report deals only with the running of the games themselves. Capital
costs of more than Pounds 140m for an athletics stadium came out of
borrowings and will be paid back over several decades from local taxes.
The report comes as the council contemplates up to 800 redundancies to
eliminate a potential Pounds 7m overspend on its budget of more than Pounds
700m. Mr Mike Bower, leader of the Labour-controlled council, last night
refused to link the losses on the games with the job cuts, saying the
budgetary problem could just as well have come from overspending on
education, housing or cleansing.
The council will consider the report on Friday, when it will go into secret
session to consider a confidential document by Mrs Pamela Gordon, its chief
executive, on the role of Mr Ray Gridley, Sheffield's director of housing.
Mr Gridley was seconded to run the games after the council took on their
management in 1990.
Previously, the idea was to keep the games at arm's length, with the company
Universiade GB set up specially to run them. But the company had constant
funding problems as it struggled to win sponsorship.
Mr Sutton says council officers failed to set up systems to monitor Mr
Gridley, and he unintentionally misled councillors about how well things
were going. There was then a failure to press for more detail. Mrs Gordon
says in her own report on the games, also published last night, that the
line between optimism and over-optimism is sometimes difficult to draw.
Mrs Gordon said last night that she saw no reason to resign but would await
councillors' reactions at Friday's meeting.
Mr Gridley said he did not accept all Mr Sutton's findings and that the
positive achievements of the games should be 'included in the balance'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
