<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / Municipal insurer runs for cover: The troubles that are
forcing MMI to look for a rescuer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOCAL government leaders are reflecting ruefully on events which led to the
possible demise of Municipal Mutual Insurance, the local-authority-owned
company. For most of its 89 years Municipal Mutual stuck to the solid but
unexciting business of insuring everything from schools to dustcarts - it is
the insurer for nine out of 10 metropolitan, district and county councils.
Now it is on the brink of insolvency after expansion into other areas of the
insurance market in the 1980s - when it frequently undercut its larger
rivals to increase market share - and a sharp increase in claims in the last
two years.
Led by Mr Andrew McLean, who resigned as chief executive earlier this year,
it focused its expansion into motor and home insurance. The group also built
up a portfolio of high-risk international commercial insurance in the London
market. Between 1987 and 1991 premium income increased from Pounds 397m to
Pounds 917m.
Mr Mike Shaw, director of finance at Gateshead Metropolitan Council, said:
'They should have stuck to basics. There was never any problem until they
were allowed to go into all these new areas.' The company had been a victim
of the 1980s enthusiasm for 'privatisation'.
Local government leaders were also unhappy about changes to the ownership
structure which gave individual policyholders similar voting rights to those
of the local authorities themselves.
The changes diluted local authority control ahead of the 1989 Local
Government Act, which forced local government to divest ownership of
commercial businesses, giving management more leeway to pursue expansion.
The expansion was followed by deterioration in trading conditions in the
insurance industry as a whole, following a spate of bad weather, recession
and crime-related losses. Municipal Mutual was exposed to rising claims on
its liability business - insuring local authorities against the cost of
legal claims for negligence.
The group paid out several million pounds to relatives of those killed in
the Hillsborough football disaster in 1989. Claims to former residents of
Staffordshire children's homes psychologically injured by the 'pindown'
disciplinary regime will amount to more than Pounds 2m. Schemes designed to
protect local authorities with tight budgets against the cost of stand-ins
for teachers absent through illness have also led to losses of millions of
pounds.
Compensation claims from individuals suffering minor injuries after
accidents on poorly maintained streets have increased sharply. Mr Henry
Croft Baker, a local authority insurance specialist with the brokers
Fenchurch, said authorities had been seen as a 'soft target' by claimants,
encouraged to claim by the increasing size of court awards.
Overall claims increased to Pounds 906m in 1991, more than three times the
level in 1987, leaving Municipal Mutual with a pre-tax loss of Pounds 132m.
After increasing provisions to pay for future claims, Municipal Mutual's net
assets - assets less liabilities - had declined to Pounds 4.9m. This left it
with a solvency margin - assets as a percentage of non-premium income - well
below minimum levels normally accepted within the industry.
Management was tightened last year when company chairman Mr Maurice
Stonefrost, former chief executive of the Greater London Council, who took
over at the end of 1990, took a more active role.
Premium rates were increased sharply, local authorities asked to retain much
larger deductibles (the portion of a claim paid by the buyer) and management
controls tightened. In April Municipal Mutual sold its commercial risks
business and closed its Australian subsidiary.
But the acute shortage of capital combined with the uncertain size of future
claims has forced more radical measures. Following Mr McLean's departure in
May, Mr Brian Wright, the retiring chief executive of Sun Alliance, was
invited in to spearhead efforts to find a buyer, while actuaries from UBS
Phillips &amp; Drew have been attempting to calculate the size of future
liabilities.
In the summer a succession of potential companies - including Britain's Sun
Alliance and Eagle Star - examined Municipal Mutual's books. Most were
scared off by the company's potential future liabilities. One executive
said: 'Although there is no black hole, the business is fundamentally
unattractive. The liabilities are just unquantifiable.'
Talks with Paris-based Garantie Groupe Mutuelle de Fonctionnaires, which
since July has pursued an interest in buying Municipal Mutual, are also
understood to have found this issue something of a sticking point.
Municipal Mutual insisted yesterday that talks would continue this week. In
the meantime some local authorities are looking for alternative cover. The
Association of Metropolitan Authorities last week advised members whose
policies came up for renewal to buy policies from other insurance companies.
Mr Croft Baker estimates that Municipal Mutual has lost as many as 5 per
cent of its local authority customers over the past five to six months.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
