<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / Ruling safeguards lift-truck jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FUTURE of manufacturing in the UK by Lancer Boss Group, the biggest
British-owned lift-truck producer, was secured yesterday after two years of
uncertainty caused by a green-belt planning row.
Mr Michael Howard, environment secretary, has granted Boss planning
permission for a project to consolidate manufacturing on one site in the
company's home town of Leighton Buzzard, Bedfordshire.
Boss manufactures in seven sites scattered across the town, and Sir Neville
Bowman-Shaw, chairman, had warned that objections to the consolidation plan
might have forced the company to relocate its manufacturing operations
overseas.
Mr Howard's decision safeguards 600 jobs in Boss's manufacturing and related
departments at Leighton Buzzard. It could also mean the creation of 500 jobs
in the town by boosting the company's status as an efficient, high-volume
producer.
Boss has manufactured lift trucks in Leighton Buzzard since 1959, and two
years ago announced the consolidation plan to remain competitive in the
cut-throat global lift-truck industry and to take advantage of growth
markets such as the Far East.
The plan involves a 37,000 sq metre extension of one of the Boss factories,
which would encroach on the green belt by 95 metres.
Local planning permission was granted last year but objections from Friends
of the Earth, the environmental pressure group, and a local preservation
society led the environment department to call in the plan, and Boss was
asked to submit a review of possible alternatives.
Mr Howard yesterday said: 'I have had to balance the benefits to the
national and local economy against the harm that will be done to the green
belt.
'I have carefully considered the evidence relating to the availability of
alternative sites, but concluded that none has been identified which would
be suitable for the purpose and available within the required timescale.'
The decision will be an immense relief for Boss employees and components
suppliers in the UK.
Over the past decade Boss has bought manufacturers of lift trucks in Spain,
Germany and Italy, all of which could have provided immediate production
capacity at the expense of running down the British plant.
Mr Trevor Bowman-Shaw, vice-chairman, said the uncertainty over the plans
would delay the start of the extension, as other Boss European factories
have had to be given priority while the planning permission was being
reviewed.
Boss expects to finalise the extension plan towards the end of next year.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
