<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / Coal contract talks delayed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEGOTIATIONS on the new contracts between British Coal and the electricity
industry have run into further delays. It is now unlikely that Mr Michael
Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary, will be able to announce them
at the Tory party conference next week, as originally planned.
Sources close to the talks said yesterday that several weeks of further
negotiation might be needed.
One of the issues delaying completion is how the risks in the contracts
should be shared between British Coal, the generators and the distribution
companies. These risks could come from actions by the electricity regulator
or the government.
There were also suggestions yesterday that the volumes of coal to be
supplied under the contracts might be further reduced. These are believed to
be about 40m tonnes a year, reducing to 30m. This compares with 65m tonnes
this year.
The government has apparently decided not to impose any political deadlines
on the talks, which are vital to the proposed privatisation of British Coal.
Previous attempts to secure a deal by a set date have all failed, and have
if anything complicated the complex negotiations. However some urgency will
begin to creep into the talks if the government is to meet its timetable of
initiating the privatisation by the end of this year.
</TEXT>
