<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (25): What makes the top
dogs tick
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MONTAGNON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A HEAD FOR BUSINESS by Corinne Simcock Kogan Page Pounds 16.95, 164 pages
WHAT MAKES a top manager tick? Corinne Simcock has tried to find out by
interviewing 13 senior British managers on how they have run their affairs
during the recession. The best corporate survival strategy, it turns out, is
to keep a firm grip on cash-flow. If costs have to be cut, the knife should
go in clean, deep and early.
That said, there is no single recipe for success. Sir Owen Green, outspoken
chairman of BTR, is dismissive of the fashion for returning to basics or
core business. He calls it 'hocus-pocus.' The core, he says, 'is 'that which
is left after the apple is eaten.' By contrast, Christopher Lewinton, whose
TI Group recently acquired the Dowty engineering concern, believes companies
should concentrate on preparing themselves for slow growth for years to
come. According to Sir Christopher Hogg of Courtaulds, 'companies survive
because they do things for their customers which are distinctive and which
their customers want. There's no other reason.'
All this sounds like good common sense - but it is hardly original. Perhaps
the fault lies in Ms Simcock's failure to draw her subjects out
sufficiently. Nor, though, do the assembled great and the good sound
particularly brilliant in their comments on everyday life. Sir Owen Green's
reservations about Europe are the kind of chatter one could hear in any Home
Counties pub.
Sir Graham, admittedly, comes across as one of the most thoughtful of the
business leaders. It is sobering to realise, as he points out, that the
Rover group spends Pounds 30m a year more on training than would be needed
if its employees had education up to German standards.
What binds these people together is an enormous sense of self-confidence
and, generally, of their own worth. Several have difficulty focusing on that
part of their contribution which is intended to examine their weaknesses.
The other factors are stamina and a sometimes astonishing dedication to the
job in hand. Mr Jon Foulds, chairman of the Halifax Building Society,
recounts that when he was at 3i, he started looking forward to Mondays as
soon as it got to Friday night. Surely, Mr Foulds, there is more to life
than that?
</TEXT>
