<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (22): The inside guide to
inside influence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DEALING WITH WHITEHALL by Philip Connelly Century Business Pounds, 208 pages
EVERY BUSINESS feels the impact of government, through decisions on economic
policy, taxation, regulation and the like. Charities, pressure groups and
trade associations have long sought to win advantages and fend off
legislative threats. Yet only recently have businesses learnt to enter the
political arena to ensure that their interests are not harmed by political
decisions.
The political battle over the future of Westland was one of the first
occasions on which lobbyists were prominently working on behalf of the major
protagonists. But the practice is fast spreading - so much so that when the
Lord Chancellor proposed reforming the legal profession, the Bar Council
employed a lobbying firm to defend the interests of barristers.
Too often, however, businesses resort to lobbying only when a threat is
perceived, rather than keeping abreast of political developments and pushing
for favourable government decisions whenever their interests are affected.
Parliament and Whitehall remain closed books for many business leaders.
Lobbyist Philip Connelly sets out to remedy this in his guide to effective
lobbying. The book offers much sensible advice on how to find out what is
going on and influence the outcome. It also contains a wealth of information
on the government machine, including helpful guides to the responsibilities
of important government departments.
Certainly there will be businesses which can use this book to do a spot of
amateur lobbying (aided, no doubt, by the recent moves to open up the
mysteries of government a little more). An intelligent young public affairs
executive could use it to gather useful intelligence, though an up-to-date
copy of Dod's Parliamentary Companion would be advisable given the speed
with which the government machine changes.
But the none-too-subtle message of the book is that high-level expertise is
essential, especially if lobbying Brussels. Since only the largest firms can
afford to employ such expertise in-house, that inevitably means using
professional lobbying firms.
Unfortunately, these can be immensely variable in quality. Some do little
more than recycle information freely available to the public in reference
books and from the House of Commons Vote Office for the benefit of clients
who pay thousands of pounds a year for the service. A chapter on how to sort
out the wheat from the chaff in choosing a lobbyist would be a valuable
addendum to any subsequent editions.
</TEXT>
