<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (19): A bitter toast to
Seagram's Mr Sam
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICHOLAS FAITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SAMUEL BRONFMAN: THE LIFE AND TIMES OF SEAGRAM'S MR SAM by Michael A
MarrusUniversity Press of New England Dollars 35
AFTER READING this authorised biography of the leader of Canada's Jewish
community I am profoundly glad my paternal grandfather never got there as he
had intended. For in Canada - more than in most non-European countries -
anti-Semitism survived the Holocaust alive and well. As late as 1947 the
country's director of immigration was still talking of the danger of
'expanding non-assimilable racial groups', and you may be sure he was not
referring to any potential Gentile threat.
Bronfman's attitude to this ingrained anti-Semitism was typical of his
generation: he simply tried to conform the harder, to make even more
obsessive efforts to prove himself (and thus Jews in general) worthy of the
marvellous society in which he - quite genuinely in his case - felt honoured
to live. Younger generations would do well not to sneer at what must now
seem like Uncle-Tomism. Unlike Bronfman and the majority of the Jewish
community (in Britain and the US as well as in Canada) they can afford to
ignore the intermittent pogroms and endemic persecution in Tsarist Russia
from which Mr Sam's family fled in the last quarter of the 19th century.
The Jewish dimension - which was inherited by his son Edgar, now president
of the World Jewish Congress - is one of the most fascinating aspects of a
biography which, although authorised, gives a rounded, and thus pretty
'wartish', portrait of an extraordinary monster - 'Mr Sam,' founder and
inspirer of one of the world's dominant liquor groups, and the only one now
not controlled from Britain.
Allowing facts to speak for themselves is a good way of getting round the
difficulties and limitations inevitable with an authorised biography -
though it helps when the younger generation does not mind the author
describing what a terrible parent the founder was.
He was absent most of the time, on his weekly commute from the family home
in Montreal to New York, and when he was at home insisted on the combination
of strict formality and unreasonably high expectations which mar the
childhood of most children of obsessive high achievers; although they did
not have to endure the outbreaks of vicious and foul-mouthed temper which
regularly marked his dealings with underlings, they also seem to have been
received fewer of the spontaneous acts of kindness of which he was also
capable.
Mr Sam was driven, obsessive, and that meant being Number One in every walk
of life, above all in the drinks business, first in North America and then
throughout the world. A member of a large and ambitious family, which had
probably been in the drinks business back in Russia (Bronf-man means
whisky-man), he was at his most ruthless when coping with competition from
his elder brother, Harry. This was open enough: Sam even started one
fraternal letter: 'Hello opposition.' Harry was pushed aside after being
unlucky enough to be the fall guy in the family's inevitable brushes with
the law - Canada being periodically subject to waves of Prohibitionist
hysteria.
But Mr Sam was also obsessive about the quality of his products; he had an
excellent palate and rightly insisted, long before it became fashionable,
that the best, most honourable (as well as, in the long term, most
profitable) policy in the liquor business was to prefer quality to quantity:
Drink Less, but Drink Better, which in Mr Sam's eyes inevitably meant
drinking one of his up-market blends, like Lord Calvert, Crown Royal or
Seven Crown, for decades the world's best-selling spirit.
As so often in these cases a firmly-held policy was also exceedingly
convenient. After Prohibition was repealed in the US in 1934, Canadian
distillers found themselves with stocks of proper straight, malt liquor
which were totally inadequate to meet the demand. So they preferred to blend
the malts, the bourbons or the rye whiskies with neutral, mass produced,
grain spirit.
Mr Sam was perfectly sincere in his belief in the superiority of blends over
straight whisky. Unlike his great rival, Lew Rosensteil, of Schenley, he
ensured that his blends were properly matured: he was obsessive about
holding adequate stocks of maturing whisky which he would not release even
on the thirstiest of markets until they were ready, and one of his greatest
triumphs was the invention of Chivas Regal, the most successful premium
blended Scotch of the post-war years.
Unfortunately Mr Marrus does not give us enough about distillation
techniques and the reason for the supposed superiority of the Seagram
blends, and he is apparently unaware of the old monster's capacity to change
with the times. The biography does not recount how in the late 1960s Mr Sam,
always on the alert for opportunity, bought Augier, the oldest firm in
Cognac, and started to build stocks of old brandies with a view to launching
Cognac's equivalent to Chivas. He may have pretended that Cognac was a
blend, but it is fundamentally different from blended whisky.
Mr Sam died before the new brand was launched, and in the confusion
following his death - his firm was notoriously unorganised, everything
depending on the old man's iron whims - his sons brought in 'marketing men'
who did not understand the liquor business. It has been left to his grandson
to fill the enormous gap in the firm's portfolio by buying Martell for more
than Pounds 600m, expenditure which would have proved unnecessary had Mr
Sam's policy been followed. You can just imagine the old bugger shouting 'I
told you so' from the grave.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IX
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-445</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CI2B1AFJFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920929
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (17): The engines that drove
civilisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By A C GRAYLING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE POWER OF THE MACHINE by R A Buchanan Viking Pounds 20, 299 pages
WHAT DRIVES the wheels of progress? The machine. What drives the machine?
Wind, fire, water, electricity, nuclear fission: even, in antiquity as in
poor countries today, the patient ox and the sweating labourer.
In this highly readable book Angus Buchanan reflects on the technological
revolution which has driven the last three centuries at an increasingly
furious gallop. This is an aspect of history which often gets ignored as we
hasten to read of political intrigues and great battles. But real historical
forces lie long and deep; as Buchanan shows, it is technology that shapes
civilisations.
A history of technology has to address itself to three issues. One concerns
the invention and development of technologies. It is difficult to fathom an
inventor's psychological processes, but it is a fair bet that they have to
be well-prepared, and faced with a problem, for ideas to spark.
Development of technologies is a more objective matter, and can be traced
historically. Here the first issue merges with the second, concerning the
spread of technology. Some hold that technological knowledge is transmitted
by travellers and traders, others that similar technologies arise
simultaneously but unconnectedly in different places. Both arguments can be
supported by historical evidence, but both offer puzzles.
The third issue concerns the social impact of technology. This is the sphere
in which technology makes its civilisation-transforming impact most felt.
Two examples illustrate the point. New agricultural technologies make food
more abundant, thus supporting population growth. This puts pressure on
social institutions, which have to change in response. A butterfly effect,
magnifying changes as they spread, flows outwards from the higher crop
yields in the fields.
Another example is military technology. When one state achieves superiority
over others, it exerts dominance; whether by conquest or influence, such
dominance changes relationships, and alters the flow of goods, wealth and
people around the world. About 1000 BC the Bronze Age gave way to the Iron
Age; the reason for the switch - once furnaces could be made hot enough to
work iron - was that iron takes a better edge than bronze. So weapons, and
axes for felling forests, became sharper; and they cut a new direction for
history.
Buchanan's main concern is with the period from 1700 AD. Since then
technological change has been extraordinarily rapid. The key is power. Power
is what makes possible any kind of making and doing, the stuff of
technology. So Buchanan begins the main part of his book with a discussion
of sources of power, from animals (including man) up to the internal
combustion engine and electricity. The importance of the 18th century as
marking a sudden acceleration in technological development is the advent of
steam power.
The idea of steam power was first mooted by Hero of Alexander in antiquity,
but it was only in the late 18th century, partly as a result of advancement
in natural science, that the idea became reality. Scientific enquiry had
offered two crucial discoveries: that the atmosphere has weight, and that a
partial vacuum can be created in a closed vessel.
It is a relatively simple matter to put these ideas to work. Place a freely
moving piston in a cylinder closed at the bottom and open at the top.
Introduce steam below the piston; condense it with a jet of cold water, thus
creating a partial vacuum, and atmospheric pressure will push the piston
down. Attach the piston to a beam to which other rods or wheels are
connected, and motion is imparted to them - to raise water, turn looms, pull
loads. The piston is raised again by the weight of the attachments to the
beam in the course of its revolution, and the process begins again.
Refinements to this simple device soon had whole landscapes of smoking
factories at work, producing goods to be whistled by rail to quaysides where
freighters lay ready to steam across the seas.
The economic and technological impulse of these developments led in an
accelerating path to other forms of engine based on more powerful and
flexible principles. Transport and communications provide examples of the
revolution which has taken place in the present century alone; but at a
cost, in pollution among other things, which makes Buchanan gravely doubt
whether it is sustainable.
From the sources of power to its uses, and from these to the effects of
technology on people, the state, and the future: Buchanan takes us on a
thought-provoking and instructive tour of the facts and problems.
He shows that anyone living reflectively in the complexities of the present
should wish to be soundly informed about technology, its history and its
meaning. His book enjoyably satisfies that wish.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VIII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-446</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CI2B1AFIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920929
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (18): The public role in
keeping the wheels turning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JANE'S URBAN TRANSPORT SYSTEMS 1992-93 edited by Chris Bushell Jane's
Information Group Pounds 135, 591 pages
URBAN TRAFFIC congestion is not a new problem, but new solutions are being
sought.
Where once planners accommodated traffic growth by building more roads, in
many towns and cities this is no longer seen as environmentally acceptable.
As a result, public transport is increasingly coming back into its own.
However, as demand for public transport grows, so does the problem of who
should pay for it. Governments cannot afford to pick up the bill, and the
difficulties of obtaining developer contributions were highlighted earlier
this year when cash-strapped Olympia &amp; York, the developer of Canary Wharf
in London's Docklands, defaulted on its planned contribution to the cost of
extending London Underground's Jubilee Line.
The solution, according to Chris Bushell in his foreword to the annual
edition of Jane's Urban Transport Systems, is to charge motorists for use of
the roads and to apply the proceeds to the provision of better public
transport. This in turn might tempt more motorists to abandon their cars.
In practice, however, political realities have discouraged the widespread
application of this idea. Hence, this comprehensive guide to the state of
urban transport around the world highlights - in sometimes depressing detail
 -a widening gap between supply and demand, a situation which is likely to
persist as long as the nettle remains to be grasped.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VIII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-447</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CI2B1AFHFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920929
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (14): The business of
history
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ST GEORGE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MYTH, HISTORY AND THE INDUSTRIALREVOLUTION by D C Coleman Hambledon Press
Pounds 32, 225 pages
FIRST, A Cambridge High Table joke about Oxford: ask an Oxford economist who
invented the term 'Industrial Revolution' and the smart reply will be
'Arnold Toynbee, who got it from Marx.' Hardly hysterical, particularly
since it was Friedrich Engels in Die Lage Englands (1844) who used the term
repeatedly; but the wit uncovers arcane disagreement in recondite quarters,
the beginnings of a battle over business history.
The question which taxes DC Coleman throughout his ten selected essays
(1953-1989) is this: 'What is business history?' Myth, History and the
Industrial Revolution strikes at industrial, economic and business history
from several angles. These densely compiled essays are explorations in the
area, conceptual accounts and statistical feats, everywhere bowed with the
fruits of learning.
There are pieces on Adam Smith, Naval Dockyards Under the Stuarts and a fine
examination of 'Proto-industrialisation.' Coleman writes indirectly and
capaciously, spreading his knowledge. An essay on Marx refers to the English
Romantics, one on 'Gentleman and Players' dealing with business competence
in Victorian England touches on Castiglione and JH Newman.
His abiding concern with business history begins with the concept of the
Industrial Revolution, born of Romanticism and Revolution, widespread in
continental Europe but slow to reach England. Without it and its heroes,
whether theoreticians like Adam Smith or practitioners such as Josiah
Wedgewood, business history would not exist.
So, what is business history, and why write it? In two essays, 'Historians
and Businessmen' and 'The Use and Abuse of Business History', Coleman makes
his pitch. He has, after all, written a three-volume history of Courtaulds
and keeps a professional interest in supporting the stock.
Business history, as Coleman sees it, is the kind of book written by Charles
Wilson on Unilever (1954, 1968) and WJ Reader on Imperial Chemical
Industries (1975), both substantial works which deliver as much about the
business environment as about the respective companies. Coleman maintains
that we can use business history to learn from the past, just as we learn
from political or social history. He sees the company, including the
nationalised industry, as the fundamental unit of economic and social
history over the last hundred years.
But company history is not business history. Access to the records of a
company, bank or firm (lawyers, accountants, architects) invariably comes
only with the company's commission to write the house history; and that can
mean censorship and limitation. Forty years ago, most business history was
of this type. The gain to the commissioning company was, and continues to be
straightforward: where a commercial publisher wants a straight return on
investment by sales, a business commissioning its own history hopes for a
return in image.
So what can and do business historians write, if not company history? Since
Wilson's 1954 book on Unilever, academic business history has turned to
industries: steel, brewing, glass, shipping, insurance, banking. Business
history has none the less divided into anecdotal inside-house history, and
turgid academic texts, all narrative and no analysis.
What business history needs now is research and writing which understand the
most important organisational unit of the economy and which recognise lines
of business influence and tradition. As George Eliot said: 'The past still
travels with us from afar, and what we have been makes us what we are.'
Coleman advocates greater, freer access to company records together with
company sponsorship of research into specific issues (just as pharmaceutical
or engineering companies support academic research) in the hope that
business history will become part of the MBA curriculum: 'Those responsible
for education in business management will be failing the needs of their
subject if they continue to ignore the lessons of the business past.' The
discipline of business history still lacks a general introduction. There is
a worthwhile book waiting to be written.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
