<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (12): Inside the black and
white market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FINANCIAL ENTERPRISE IN SOUTH AFRICA SINCE 1950 edited by Stuart Jones
Macmillan Pounds 45, 316 pages
A STROLL around the streets of central Johannesburg confirms one of the most
enduring truths - and cliches - about South Africa: the extent to which
First and Third Worlds exist alongside each other.
At the heart of the town lies Bank City, the new corporate headquarters of
First National Bank (formerly Barclays), spanning four blocks and breaking
new ground in corporate machismo. All around it, however, are thousands of
black street hawkers, selling their small wares - tobacco, sweets, fruit -
for cash, and operating beyond the sophisticated systems which banks like
First National offer.
Stuart Jones's book, consisting of 12 essays, is a competent exposition of
how this well-developed financial infrastructure evolved over the past 40
years. It includes monetary and fiscal policy overviews, a look at the
growth of indigenous institutions such as the Afrikaans bank Volkskas, the
development of oil, merchant banking and hire purchase sectors, and a look
at the growth of the stock exchange.
Although Jones himself contributes in an accessible and interesting fashion,
some of the other contributions are rather stolid and certainly only of
specialist interest. And while the book warrants a place on the shelves of
committed South Africa watchers, its utility would have been enhanced, given
the rapid pace of transition underway, had some effort been made to
synthesise the past and the future.
There are, for example, pregnant hints of disapproval about the
controversial subject of concentration of control on the Johannesburg Stock
Exchange, but no attempt is made to analyse the cogency of arguments about
pyramids and concentration, and to predict how this important issue will
develop.
Long lead times have also left the book curiously dated in parts. Thus the
chapter about monetary policy, for example, was completed before Dr Chris
Stals stook over as governor nearly three years ago. His single-minded fight
against inflation, and the political freedom he has been given to pursue
this difficult task, have arguably been the main economic features of the
recent past. You would not know it from this book.
Likewise, the chapter about the Development Bank of South Africa strikes the
wrong note by concentrating on its apartheid origins and close links with
government. Jones neglects the remarkable evolution of the past few years
whereby the bank has developed a considerable reputation as a source of
non-partisan developmental expertise, to the extent that the African
National Congress (ANC) has used it as a source of input in developing
economic policy. This new orientation was recently illustrated by the way in
which the nomination of ex-Finance Minister Mr Barend du Plessis as chairman
of the bank was scuppered through both internal and external pressure.
The book was also completed too soon to take adequate account of the
important Deposit Taking Institutions (DTI) Act passed early last year which
put banks and building societies on to the same legislative footing and
brought South Africa into line with international capital adequacy
requirements. This precipitated major rationalisation in the banking sector,
leading to the formation of ABSA, the country's largest banking group.
A related, curious omission is the decision not to write about the massive
growth of the life offices movement in South Africa during the 19802, when
their ability to provide real returns in an inflationary environment saw a
huge shift in savings flows towards them. Both on grounds of innovation and
influence - the manner in which they manage their huge funds is already a
point of political contention - this sector deserved attention.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VI
