<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / The FT Review of Business Books (10): We are all consumers
now
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CONSUMERIST MANIFESTO: ADVERTISING IN POST-MODERN TIMES by Martin
Davidson Routledge Pounds 35/Pounds 10.99, 217 pages
PERHAPS the only comfort to be drawn from the UK's recession is that it has
stemmed the avalanche of meretricious books about advertising, public
relations and marketing generally - Lord knows, there are enough of them
around. But useful books on advertising still manage to find a publisher and
fortunately that includes the The Consumerist Manifesto.
Despite a thoroughly opaque, misleading title - probably invented by a
public relations team which has not read the book but is desperate to find
an audience - The Consumerist Manifesto has appeared at a time when the
advertising world is still busily examining its own navel, wondering if its
immediate future will be as commercially appalling as its recent past.
Davidson's analysis of what advertising does and how it does it weaves a
sometimes inebriated path between academic and industrial sources. But he
does a good job of unpicking the ponderous anti-advertising moralisms of
left-inclined culture-watchers - such as Raymond Williams  - and usefully
reminds us that, after all, practitioners of advertising are often very
intelligent and have a powerful influence in contemporary society.
We ought to frame the kind of absurdity otherwise intelligent people commit
when they dabble in fields beyond them. Here is Umberto Eco: 'For a Milanese
bank clerk a TV ad for a refrigerator represents a stimulus to buy, but for
an unemployed peasant in Calabria the same image means a confirmation of a
world of prosperity that doesn't belong to him and that he must conquer.
That is why I believe TV advertising in depressed countries functions as a
revolutionary message.'
The irony is that such half-baked thinking is precisely what leftist critics
of advertising and consumerism normally accuse advertising of being
responsible for.
Davidson balances their miscomprehensions of the advertising process with a
challenging polemic as to the essence of contemporary society. We are all
consumers now, he argues: 'Consumption is now the basic mode for all
activity in our society, not reading, not using, not appreciating, not
participating, not producing but consuming . . . built into this is the
demand that the world accommodate us better, that we consume it more not
less; in other words we consume aspirationally.'
In other words, though Davidson does not make this point explicitly, we have
moved from being swayed by the unique selling point (USP) of the product to
being persuaded by its ESP, or emotional selling point, and the best
advertising, in the UK at least, has moved ground recently to reflect that
subtle but crucial socio-cultural change.
That is a useful insight which advertisers and advertising agencies are
increasingly grasping and exploring. To bemoan the cultural shifts which
underlie the move towards widening consumerist mentality, and to sneer at
advertising - the most visible expression of consumer aspiration, is to spit
into the wind.
The Consumerist Manifesto is a timely and, though sometimes quite
derivative, a very useful summary of most of the key intellectual issues
underlying the functions and methods of advertising, itself one of the most
complicated and powerful forms of human communication.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page V
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-453</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CI2B1AFBFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920929
