<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / (CORRECTED) The FT Review of Business Books (21): The
Confucian way to excellence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LINDA BILMES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Correction (published 30th September 1992) appended to this article.
THE COMPLETE BOOK OF BUSINESS ETIQUETTE THE ESSENTIAL GUIDE TO GETTING AHEAD
IN BUSINESS by Lynne Brennan and David Block Piatkus Books Pounds 8.99, 185
pages
IMAGINE TRYING to run a factory with 60,000 employees, required to produce
enough nails for one billion people. You cannot fire anyone, you cannot
raise wages, you cannot even quit (though you can be tossed back to
peasant-servitude for failing to meet the annual nail quota). Information is
scarce, spare parts are unavailable, and half the foremen cannot read. How
on earth do Chinese managers manage?
Malcolm Warner sheds some light on this mystery in his fascinating study,
How Chinese Managers Learn, the first book to examine management and
industrial training in China.
A Fellow of Wolfson College, Cambridge, Professor Warner traces the
development of management training in China since 1984, when the Central
Committee set the goal of creating 'a mighty contingent of managerial and
technical cadres'. The book examines the characteristics of Chinese
management and reviews the programmes put in place to train managers:
courses, curriculi, examinations, faculty, funding and links to industrial
enterprises and government institutions.
As Professor Warner points out, trying to teach one billion people to
produce things in huge enterprises is no easy task, not least in a country
where the Cultural Revolution wiped out a generation of managers and
trainers.
Nevertheless, the 1980s economic reforms forced China to accept that a
successful, productive economy requires a trained workforce. Since only 1
per cent of the Chinese population is admitted to higher education (the
figure is 9 per cent in India and 30 per cent in Japan), the task is
enormous. Moreover, the whole idea of training managers sits uncomfortably
with ancient Chinese traditions, such as absolute respect for one's elders.
So China embarked upon a quest to teach modern technological skills with a
Confucian twist.
Professor Warner describes (in painstaking detail) the various schemes that
have been instituted. There are senior executive training centres (for
managers of large factories) in six large cities: Beijing, Chengdu, Fuzhhou,
Shanghai, Tianjin and Wuhan. Universities conduct programmes ranging from
operations effectiveness and managerial economics to management of
pharmaceutical enterprises. The World Bank, western universities and other
western institutions participate in many of these programmes. There is even
a China-European Community Joint MBA programme, which the book examines in
depth.
The important question is whether all this training has made a difference.
The book suggests that results are mixed. Efforts to create a truly dynamic
managerial caste have been hindered by the Confucian element, which reveres
the instructor and expects passive subordination from the student. Professor
Warner writes that 95 per cent of senior managers pass the main examination
because it would be too embarrassing for the state to send them back home if
they flunked.
On the other hand, management training has become immensely popular in
China, attracting top-calibre students and professors. Every bright Chinese
youth wants an MBA these days. And with Guangdong Province growing at 15 per
cent per annum, perhaps we should send a few more Westerners to study over
there.
CORRECTION
In Tuesday's Business Books Review, an incorrect book title appeared in the
review headlined 'The Confucian way to excellence' on page 10. The book
reviewed is How Chinese Managers Learn, by Malcolm Warner (Macmillan, Pounds
40, 211 pages).
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page X
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-471</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CI2B1AEMFT</PROFILE>
