<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 92 / International Company News: Goodyear sees improvement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GOODYEAR, the last surviving large US-owned tyre company, said it expected
to achieve third-quarter earnings higher than the Dollars 1.01 per share
recorded in the same period last year.
The Akron-based Goodyear, which also said its chief financial officer
resigned yesterday, forecast another quarterly sales record, with total
revenues coming at around the second quarter level of more than Dollars 3bn.
In the third quarter of 1991, Goodyear earned Dollars 59.1m on sales of
Dollars 2.8bn.
Goodyear said its improved third-quarter results had been helped by cost
containment, the successful introduction of new products, improved
productivity and a strengthened distribution network.
On Wall Street, investors seemed unimpressed at the prospect of only
slightly better third-quarter revenues from Goodyear. The company's share
price closed Dollars  5/8 lower at Dollars 58 3/8 after dipping to Dollars
57 7/8 .
Mr Oren Shaffer, the Goodyear chief financial officer, will meanwhile resign
from his position on Thursday 'to pursue other interests'.
He will be replaced by Mr Samir Gibara, a vice-president of strategic
planning and business development.
Goodrich, the aerospace and specialty chemicals company that in 1988 sold
off its tyre division, said its third-quarter earnings would be
significantly below market expectations.
The Ohio company said it was likely to report only a modest profit for the
quarter. Analysts had been expecting Goodrich to earn Dollars 10m, or 30
cents a share. But Goodrich said the earnings would be well below the second
quarter's Dollars 13.1m, or 43 cents a share.
Mr John Ong, chairman, said the specialty chemicals and polyvinyl chloride
businesses depended in large measure on the strength of the US economy.
</TEXT>
