<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 92 / Schools' opt-out rate is low
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT'S campaign to persuade schools in England and Wales to opt
out of local authority supervision has so far made little impact, with only
50 schools planning to ballot on opting-out in the coming month.
Local education authorities are responsible for more than 21,000 schools in
England. Only 277 have opted out so far. That number rises to 440 if all
schools at some point in the opting-out process are included.
Mr John Patten, education secretary, is targeting secondary schools as the
most likely candidates for grant-maintained status, under which schools
receive a lump sum - often larger than that available from their local
education authority - determined by the Education Department and are free to
spend it largely as they want.
His statement last week that financial advantages for grant-maintained
schools would continue was a deliberate attempt to increase the opt-out
rate. But the education white paper, published in July, appeared to signal
an end to the incentives, except for schools in low-spending authorities,
and tight public spending will be a serious constraint.
</TEXT>
