<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 92 / Gains tax far too high, says think tank
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CAPITAL gains tax is 'seriously flawed' and the rate at which it is levied
should be halved in order to increase revenues, according to the Institute
of Economic Affairs, the free-market think tank, Emma Tucker writes.
Five analysts of tax systems say in an IEA pamphlet published yesterday that
the existing UK rate of 40 per cent - among the highest in the world - may
be more than twice the rate that would maximise government revenue.
'The tax yield from CGT in Britain would probably increase substantially if
the rate were cut to 20 per cent or less,' they write.
The IEA claims that every instance of a capital gains tax rate cut in the US
has been 'rapidly followed by a significant increase in capital gains
realisations and by higher taxes paid on those gains'. It accuses Lord
Lawson, who as chancellor was responsible for 1988 reforms of capital gains
tax, of ignoring supply-side arguments that lower taxes would boost activity
and hence revenue.
The pamphlet's authors argue that the taxation of venture capital is heavy -
even prohibitive - in the UK, a fact which gives other countries in the
European Community a competitive advantage.
A Discredited Tax, Institute of Economic Affairs, 2 Lord North Street,
London, SW1P 3LB. Pounds 7.95.
</TEXT>
