<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 92 / Cadbury attacks old-boy network
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH COMPANIES should adopt an objective approach and appoint to their
boards more women and others from a wider variety of backgrounds, Sir Adrian
Cadbury said yesterday.
Sir Adrian is chairman of Pro Ned, the organisation which promotes the role
of non-executive directors. The body yesterday called on company chairmen to
abandon the 'old-boy network'.
Sir Adrian said shareholders are also entitled to full information about all
aspects of directors' pay, and standards should be openly debated and
agreed.
Writing in Pro Ned's 10th annual review, Sir Adrian said companies should
'look beyond the limited circle which the chairman and their boards normally
have in mind'. He said they would benefit by drawing on a wider pool of
talent, including divisional directors of leading companies, academics and
those with extensive management experience in the public and voluntary
sectors.
Mr Colin St Johnston, Pro Ned managing director, said a recent survey by the
organisation had shown that 86 per cent of senior business people and
investors were dissatisfied with the appointment process of non-executive
directors, and less than a quarter of companies prepared a job profile for
these appointments.
Sir Adrian said that selection should involve the board as a whole through a
nomination committee. He said the process should begin by discussing the
skills and experience which would complement those of existing executives.
He said one of the main themes running through the report issued earlier
this year by a committee on the financial aspects of corporate governance,
which he chaired, was the need for able, independent-minded, non-executive
directors. He stressed that non-executives were an integral part of the
board rather than having a separate existence.
Sir Adrian favours changing 'non-executive director' to the US term 'outside
director' - 'an accurate description without overtones'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
