<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 92 / DPP demands strict time limits in fraud trials
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MRS BARBARA MILLS QC, director of public prosecutions and former head of the
Serious Fraud Office, yesterday called for radical action to tackle the
problems of long fraud trials.
She told the Bar's annual conference in London that the country could no
longer afford to live with the present system. Public confidence had been
badly damaged by the Blue Arrow and Guinness cases and needed to be restored
urgently.
Mrs Mills said time limits should be imposed on trials, with none taking
more than two months. 'There are some trials which advance nowhere day after
day,' she said. 'What are we doing wasting the public's money in this way?
This has got to stop.'
Trial judges should have the power to decide how much time should be spent
on each issue in a trial, Mrs Mills continued. Barristers should be limited
to half an hour on each issue. A simple fraud offence should be introduced
and the prosecution should be obliged to produce short indictments.
Plea-bargaining should be encouraged, Mrs Mills said. At the moment the
justice system achieved very little for victims of fraud. In the US
plea-bargaining had been instrumental in recovering millions of dollars for
victims.
She also proposed that prosecution and defence should be compelled to
co-operate in identifying the issues for trial by early disclosure of their
cases during pre-trial hearings. The intention behind the special pre-trial
procedure for fraud cases introduced by the 1987 Criminal Justice Act was
excellent, but did not work because it had no teeth.
Defendants who did not co-operate should not be allowed to give evidence and
cross-examine at the trial on issues about which they had not disclosed
their positions during pre-trial hearings.
Mrs Mills was supported by Mr Justice Henry, the Guinness trial judge. He
called for enforced pre-trial disclosure, for time limits, for trials to
begin with a summary of the issues by the judge and for the jury to have a
list of witnesses and a timetable.
Sir Bryan Carsberg, director-general of fair trading, told the conference
the predominance of European law over national law was proving a growing
constraint on action to promote competition in the UK.
Trying to inject competition into the supply of beer following the 1989
Monopolies and Mergers Commission report, for example, was hindered by the
possibility of a conflict between beer orders under the Fair Trading Act and
an EC exemption on exclusive purchasing agreements. The UK also appeared to
be constrained by the exemption in action it could take to modify the
distribution system for cars. He criticised 'restrictive distribution
arrangements where the effect is to ban certain kinds of retail activity.'
</TEXT>
