<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 92 / Close race in NEC ballot
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE OUTCOME of elections to Labour's ruling national executive committee
will be announced today with Mr Bryan Gould reportedly locked in a close
three-horse race with Mr Tony Benn, the veteran leftwinger, and Mr Tony
Blair, the shadow home secretary.
Unconfirmed reports in Blackpool suggested last night that Mr Neil Kinnock,
the former leader, and Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, are set to
cruise home in the annual ballot.
But with only one vacancy - left by the outgoing Mr Gerald Kaufman - that
would mean at least one other occupant of the seven-member constituency
section must fall out.
Speculation on the eve of the conference was that Mr Benn, second to Mr
Kaufman, who came last in 1991, is the most vulnerable. But some also
believe that a strong challenge from Mr Blair, a newcomer, means that Mr
Gould, who came fifth last year, could also lose his seat.
Although the outcome of the voting will have little influence on the overall
political composition of the national executive - it is firmly supportive of
the leadership - it will be closely perused as an indicator of the mood in
the constituency parties.
If Mr Gould, who suffered a humiliating defeat in the race for the
leadership, is knocked off by Mr Blair, it will consolidate the position of
the pro-Maastricht loyalists close to Mr Smith's leadership.
A defeat for Mr Benn would also be regarded as ending an era for the left
wing. In recent years he and Mr Dennis Skinner, the leftwing MP for
Bolsover, have formed a two-man 'rejectionist' front, voting or tabling
motions opposed to the leadership's policies.
Mr Gould's resignation from the shadow cabinet yesterday should have little
bearing on the race as constituency delegates are, in theory, bound by
ballots completed some time ago.
Nonetheless, with European issues now provoking a schism in the party,
analysts will be carefully assessing the consequences of the results on
policy positions to be taken by the national executive in coming months.
The election last year of Mr Kaufman, a well-known rightwinger, was widely
seen as a consequence of the introduction of a one-member-one-vote balloting
system and the influence of television, both of which are thought to favour
those with the most media exposure.
