<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 92 / Meeting of minds behind Smith's strategy: Emma Tucker
identifies members of the 'academic panel' that advises MPs on policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN Messrs John Smith and Gordon Brown stand up this week to address the
party conference, Labour's hotch-potch of economic advisers will doubtless
breathe a sigh of relief that it is not their task to defend the pound's
recent upheavals.
One of the gurus has been there before. In 1967, when Mr Harold Wilson, the
then prime minister, devalued sterling, Mr Andrew Graham was assistant to
the cabinet's economic advisers. Long associated with the Labour party, the
Oxford economics don now works part-time as the convener of a group of City
and academic economists who gather on an irregular basis to exchange views
and give advice to Mr Smith and Mr Brown.
The approach differs from Mr Smith's predecessor Mr Neil Kinnock, who relied
almost solely on the advice of Mr John Eatwell, a Cambridge don, now on his
way to the Lords as a Labour peer.
'The objective of the group is to get in different ideas,' says Mr Gerry
Holtham, one of the group's City members. 'John is a lawyer and likes to
weigh the evidence.'
But the name most closely associated with Mr Smith is that of Mr Graham.
Sympathisers describe him as a pragmatic, realistic economist in tune with
the modern party, while adversaries stick to the label 'old-fashioned
Keynesian'.
Undergraduates, taught by the 50-year old windsurfing enthusiast at Balliol
remember his dismissal of Conservative economic policies as 'all this
monetary nonsense'.
Mr Chris Allsop of Oxford, another member of Labour's 'academic panel' - as
he prefers to call it - says the group is united by pro-European sentiment,
even if it represents a range of views.
Mr Gavyn Davies, chief economist of Goldman Sachs in London, who was tutored
by Mr Graham at Balliol, is at the end of a phone for instant clarification
or explanation of City manoeuvrings. Mr Holtham of Shearson Lehman, the
investment bank in London and Mr Neil MacKinnon, who recently moved to
Citibank are also included at the meetings.
The group also includes a number of rather tight-lipped academics from
Oxford, Cambridge and the London School of Economics. These include Mr
Allsop, Prof Meghnad Desai, professor of economics at the LSE, and on an
even more informal basis, Mr Ian Begg, Mr John Wells and Professor Wynne
Godley from the Department of Applied Economics at Cambridge.
It is early days for Mr Smith as leader and whether he expands his coterie
of advisers remains to be seen. Meanwhile, another meeting of the 'panel'
has been called for next month, giving Labour, like the government, the
opportunity to come up with a brand-new economic strategy.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
