<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 92 / Rebel's lost cause brings about his predictable exit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NO ONE was surprised by Mr Bryan Gould's decision yesterday to quit the
shadow cabinet. More of his colleagues than will admit it publicly will
lament his departure from the opposition front bench.
After his defeat by Mr John Smith in July's leadership election Mr Gould was
offered the health or education portfolios - two of the most important for
Labour in opposition.
Instead he opted to shadow the unfortunate Mr David Mellor at National
Heritage. His friends judged, rightly, that Mr Gould had decided that his
career in the new Labour team would be short.
Throughout the leadership contest it was obvious that his views on Europe,
on the exchange rate mechanism, and on economic management could not for
long be contained within the orthodoxy of Mr John Smith's shadow cabinet.
In the wake of sterling's retreat from the ERM and the Yes vote in the
French referendum on Maastricht, his criticism of Labour's support for the
ERM and the treaty had become increasingly strident.
He was briefly silent after the shadow cabinet last week agreed a common
position. But by then he had decided to resign, delaying the decision only
to avoid overshadowing Mr Smith's parliamentary debut against Mr John Major.
His clash with the leadership was not new. After a starring role in Mr Neil
Kinnock's election campaign in 1987, he found that antipathy towards
European federalism and his espousal of reflationary policies clashed with
the party's desperate quest for respectability.
The rise of Mr Gordon Brown and Mr Tony Blair in Labour's embrace of the
market and Europe saw Mr Gould shifted outside Mr Kinnock's kitchen cabinet.
He opposed the decision to back ERM membership at what he termed a
'ludicrous' rate and in effect to support the government over Maastricht.
Free yesterday of the constraints of collective responsibility, Mr Gould
displayed the depths of that antagonism. He was scathing about Maastricht as
a 'breathtaking and audacious attempt' to ensure that bankers rather than
politicians gained permanent hold over Europe's economies. The ERM had been
revealed 'for what it aways was - just another means to try to defy economic
reality'.
Many in his party regard such views as eccentric. Mr Roy Hattersley, the
former deputy leader and another of Labour's serious political thinkers,
urged him yesterday morning to give up his 'championship of lost causes'.
Others, possessed still with the search for respectability, regard him as
damaging and dangerous. If his resignation is followed today by defeat in
the annual elections to the national executive, the 53-year-old MP for
Dagenham will face a long spell in the political wilderness.
But still others will agree with the judgment offered by Mr Hattersley
before yesterday's events: 'Mr Gould is by intellect, temperament and
training the shadow cabinet member most qualified to argue Labour's
ideological case.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
