<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 92 / Major fights split on Europe: Government hopes for treaty
ratification may rest on 'subsidiarity' deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR faced renewed divisions within his cabinet over European
integration yesterday amid signs that the government's hopes for
ratification of the Maastricht treaty now rest on an EC-wide agreement to
devolve more authority from Brussels.
As the government sought vainly to re-establish a semblance of unity around
its European policy, ministers said that a declaration underwriting the
principle of 'subsidiarity' could be signed at the Edinburgh summit in
December.
The declaration, which would be attached to the Maastricht agreement, would
give substance to the brief reference in the treaty on the need to
decentralise decision-making.
Mr Major, who will press the idea in separate meetings on Wednesday with Mr
Francois Mitterrand, the French president, and Mr Poul Schluter, the Danish
prime minister, hopes the commitment will reassure enough Tory waverers to
allow him to press ahead with ratification.
The ministers said that the need to persuade Denmark to reverse its No vote
to Maastricht and the mood of public opinion throughout the Community should
persuade EC leaders at next month's emergency summit in Birmingham to give
the British presidency a mandate to draft such a declaration.
But the scale of Mr Major's task in filling the policy vacuum left by
sterling's enforced departure from the exchange rate mechanism was
underlined by the discordant notes sounded again yesterday by ministers and
senior Tory MPs.
Mr Michael Howard, the environment secretary, appeared to accept that
Britain's reluctance to set a time-frame for sterling's return to the ERM
could prompt an inner-core of countries based around Germany and France to
establish a fast-track to monetary union.
But, speaking on ITV's Walden programme, Mr Howard insisted that 'British
interests' would be paramount in deciding the government's stance. He added:
'If others choose to go at a different pace and choose to put in place
arrangements which are not suitable to us . . . we must take our decisions
on the basis of what is best for the British people.'
Those comments, along with a statement that sterling's re-entry to the ERM
would be considered only after the mechanism had been reformed, jarred with
enthusiastically pro-European statements by two other ministers.
Mr John Gummer, the agriculture secretary, told BBC Radio: 'There is no
future for Britain in some sideline. We are in the centre of Europe and we
intend to stay there.'
Disputing Mr Howard's comment that the suspension of ERM membership offered
opportunities for Britain, Mr Gummer said that the real issue was whether
the government wanted to be buffeted by the effect of strong economies and
currencies with no say in the decisions shaping events.
That view was echoed by Mr Tristan Garel-Jones, the Foreign Office minister
responsible for Europe, who said that failure to ratify Maastricht would be
a 'humiliation' for Britain.
But Sir Marcus Fox, chairman of the influential 1922 committee of
Conservative backbench MPs, was among a succession of senior Tories ready to
cast doubt on support for both Maastricht and the ERM.
With other opinion polls showing the strength of feeling against European
integration, there were also calls from a number of MPs for the government
to 'get a grip' on its strategy.
Editorial Comment, Page 22
Ministers aim to boost ERM confidence, Page 24
</TEXT>
