<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 92 / Gould quits shadow cabinet to oppose Maastricht
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BATTLE over the Maastricht treaty finally engulfed the Labour party
yesterday when Mr Bryan Gould shattered the leadership's fragile truce on
Europe by quitting the shadow cabinet.
His resignation from the post of heritage spokesman - on the eve of the
party's annual conference in Blackpool - boosted growing opposition to the
leadership's pro-Maastricht policy.
It also cast a pall over the conference that senior party officials had
hoped would capitalise on Conservative disarray on Europe and rally support
to Mr John Smith in his first appearance as leader.
Senior party figures and union leaders last night expressed open anger with
the timing of Mr Gould's decision, arguing that he had seriously underminded
Labour at a moment when the Conservatives were on the defensive.
Mr Gould's widely anticipated resignation frees him to act as standard
bearer for those opposing any return to the exchange rate mechanism and to
head the growing campaign for a referendum on the Maastricht treaty.
In an exchange of letters with Mr Smith, he said he no longer felt able to
reconcile his 'strongly held views on the economy and the future of Europe'
with his obligation to uphold collective responsibility for shadow cabinet
decisions. 'I am accordingly, and with deep regret, obliged to resign from
the shadow cabinet,' he wrote.
In reply, Mr Smith, who trounced Mr Gould by a ratio of nine to one in the
leadership election this summer, acknowledged that in the light of the
'clear decision taken by the shadow cabinet on policy towards Europe' it was
impossible for him to stay on.
The resignation came amid mounting evidence that Labour MPs are increasingly
divided over the party's response to the Maastricht treaty and Britain's
suspension of its ERM membership. The official stance - similar to that of
Mr John Major - rejects any resumption of the Commons debate on the
ratification of Maastricht until the Danes have clarified how they plan to
proceed.
Labour also opposes a return to the ERM until an industry policy is in place
and agreements are reached with other EC countries on reforming the system.
However, Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, said yesterday that Labour
supported a system of 'managed but flexible exchange rates' and rejected a
free-floating pound.
Evidence of Labour MPs' disquiet emerged in a poll of 100 MPs conducted by
the BBC's On The Record programme. A total of 42 opposed ratification of the
treaty, 19 wanted amendments and only 25 backed the pact. Forty six backed a
referendum with 44 against.
Today, the conference will debate a resolution demanding a referendum. By
allowing the motion, which is certain to be defeated, Labour leaders hope to
undermine future attempts by MPs to press for a plebiscite.
Observer, Page 23
</TEXT>
