<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 92 / Concern grows for future of troubled council insurer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Department of Trade and Industry is closely watching the slow progress
of rescue talks for Municipal Mutual Insurance, the troubled insurer owned
by UK local authorities, amid concern about its survival prospect.
The worries about MMI - the UK's ninth largest general insurer - have
intensified since the circulation of a negative assessment by Touche Ross,
the accountancy firm, and speculation that talks between MMI and its
prospective partner, La Garantie Mutuelle des Fonctionaires (GMF), are
foundering.
The French insurer is part of the Eurosafe consortium of European insurance
companies.
Mr Brian Wright, who became MMI's chief executive in May, yesterday denied
reports that the merger talks had collapsed.
'I am going to Paris this week to continue with these discussions,' he said.
The talks were protracted because the transfer of MMI's business was
complex. 'We have to ensure the transfer is effected in the best way to
protect the interests of policyholders.'
MMI ran into difficulties because claims by councils in 1990 and 1991 proved
far greater than expected, partly because of a big rise in arson attacks on
schools and a growing tendency among individuals to take legal action
against local authorities.
Its net assets declined from Pounds 287.9m at the end of 1990 to less than
Pounds 5m at the end of 1991.
The prospect of MMI's collapse, unless it quickly agrees a takeover, is
viewed with concern by local councils. If the insurer foundered, it is
unlikely that their claims would be met in full. MMI insures over 80 per
cent of local authorities.
Local authorities are not protected by the safety net of the Policyholders
Protection Act, which safeguards policyholders in the event of an insurance
company's default.
MMI announced in July that it was in talks with GMF.
The Department of Trade and Industry, which regulates insurers, said
yesterday that it was premature to speculate what would happen if a merger
was not agreed.
'We understand an agreement was reached in principle between MMI and GMF in
July,' it said. 'The department has been closely in touch with negotiations
ever since.'
However, the report by Touche Ross, which was commissioned by the
associations for county, metropolitan and district councils, is believed to
say that the DTI will insist that the group ceases trading unless the
takeover with GMF goes ahead quickly.
</TEXT>
