<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 92 / UK Company News: Sphere raises Dollars 4m and wins its
independence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SPHERE, the California video game company controlled by the late Robert
Maxwell through a Liechtenstein charitable trust, has won its independence.
The fast-growing company that has produced popular games, such as an F-16
flight simulator, has raised Dollars 4m from new investors for additional
marketing and development and buying out shares formerly held by Swico, a
charitable trust which was in effect its parent.
Earlier this year it emerged that Sphere, which trades under the name
Spectrum HoloByte, appeared to be a private Maxwell company beyond the reach
of Arthur Andersen, administrators to Mr Maxwell's private interests.
The negotiations over the future of Sphere have involved Arthur Andersen. As
a result in return for the Swico shares Dollars 2.3m was paid into an escrow
account and a further provision of Dollars 4m in preferred shares set aside
to cover any further unexpected liabilities.
Before the re-financing package was put together all Maxwell appointees to
the company were removed.
Mr Gilman Louie, president and chief executive of Spectrum HoloByte, said:
'This financing positions the company to work with our new partners in
bringing products and technologies to the industry.'
</TEXT>
