<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 92 / Block votes are fair, says Morris
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS and DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LEADER of Britain's largest union yesterday warned Labour to resist
pressure for rapid moves to cut its links with the unions amid dispute among
leading trade unionists on the future of the block vote.
Mr Bill Morris, general secretary of the TGWU general union, said yesterday
he backed the move to cut the block vote from 90 per cent to 70 per cent of
conference votes, but added that it should remain more or less in its
existing form.
Trade unionists are not yet agreed on the size of the cut to make in the
block vote. 'It seems to be the season for 'hip-shooting' but we want to
resist that because the future of the Labour party is more important than
one day's headlines,' Mr Morris said. He said block votes were 'fair votes'.
A review group on links with the unions is due to report to next year's
conference. It is unlikely that a single member of that review group
supports a complete break in the relationship. However, there is a consensus
emerging in favour of removing union influence from electing the Labour
leader and from the selection of local candidates.
The principal dispute remains how far to reduce the influence of union votes
at the conference. Yesterday the AEEU engineering and electrical union,
which is at the opposite end of the argument from Mr Morris, proposed
cutting the union vote to 31 per cent, increasing the constituency vote to
46 per cent and giving MPs and MEPs 20 per cent between them.
Under the AEEU plan, unions would get one vote for every 10,000 members who
pay the political levy, but eventually the size of the union vote would
depend on the number of individual party members in a union.
Separately, the GMB general union repeated its plan to cut the block vote to
50 per cent and put forward a plan to allow union members who pay the
political levy to become 'associate members' of constituency Labour parties
with a role in selecting parliamentary candidates.
Mr John Edmonds, GMB general-secretary, expressed scepticism about the
AEEU's plan to reform the block vote. 'I understand that this (the AEEU
plan) is a working document within the AEEU and I think that is how it
should be regarded,' he said.
A composite motion on union links, backed yesterday by the national
executive committee and to be debated by the conference on Wednesday,
expresses 'strong support for the continuation of the party's links with the
trade unions' and regrets 'ill-informed and malignly intentioned criticisms
of the trade union/Labour party link'.
But, while recognising the financial contribution of the trade unions to the
Labour party, the motion calls for 'structures to be as democratic as
possible to encourage greater involvement of individual party members and
levy-paying members of affiliated organisations'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10
