FT  26 SEP 92 / UK Company News: Second payment for B&amp;C creditors
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Creditors of British &amp; Commonwealth Holdings, the financial services group
which collapsed in June 1990 with debts of about Pounds 1bn after heavy
losses by its leasing subsidiary, Atlantic Computers, are to be given a
second payment.
B&amp;C Holdings' creditors will each receive a payment of Pounds 110m,
amounting to 5p in the pound, bringing the total they have received so far
to 10p in the pound.
Creditors of B&amp;C Group Finance, who were paid 14p earlier in the year, are
also to receive a further payment in early October, though the
administrators have not said how much it will be.
Both groups have fared badly compared with the creditors of British &amp;
Commonwealth Merchant Bank who have now been paid a total of 78p in the
pound.
