FT  26 SEP 92 / International Company News: A&amp;P hit by provision for
Isosceles
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GREAT Atlantic and Pacific Tea Company, one of the biggest US supermarket
operators, saw quarterly profits slide for a second consecutive quarter,
writes Karen Zagor in New York.
Net income for the second quarter ended September 12 was Dollars 7.64m, or
20 cents a share, compared with Dollars 14.5m, or 38 cents a share a year
earlier. Sales declined less dramatically, to Dollars 2.43bn in the latest
quarter from Dollars 2.65bn a year ago.
For the first six months, A&amp;P's underlying net income fell to Dollars 30.4m,
or 80 cents a share from Dollars 50.7m, or Dollars 1.33, the previous year.
The company, which is 53 per cent owned by Germany's Tengelmann group, took
an Dollars 89.2m provision in the first half of this year to cover potential
losses on its equity stake in Isosceles, which owns the UK Gateway grocery
chain.
The write-off, and one-time accounting items, contributed to a net loss in
the first half of Dollars 149.8m, or Dollars 3.92 a share. There were no
significant extraordinary items in the same period of 1991.
