<HEADLINE>
FT  26 SEP 92 / Finance &amp; The Family: Doctors' dilemma on tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARBARA ELLIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DOCTORS may face a taxing problem. Since the beginnings of the National
Health Service, GPs have been classed as self-employed and taxed under
schedule D, even though some of their circumstances might suggest relegation
to the less generous schedule E.
Dr Joe Neary, a Cambridgeshire GP, experienced what he saw as a challenge to
the tax status of GPs when he applied for approval of a profit-related pay
scheme for his four employees. 'I got a negative response from the Revenue,
based on the argument that the enterprise of general practice is entirely
government funded,' he told a medical magazine, adding: 'I saw no point in
chasing it through the courts as this might be counter-productive if GPs'
schedule D tax status was questioned.'
Instead, Neary told the Financial Times, he went through his own political
channels. He made informal contact with Gillian Shephard, the employment
secretary who is MP for Norfolk SW. She confirmed what the Revenue had said.
The profit-related pay issue became academic for him as, in the event, his
first year in practice yielded far less than expected. But he says that if
he nets a profit next year of more than Pounds 42,000, the national intended
standard, he will pay staff bonuses reflecting their extra dedication. Since
his scheme will not have been approved, however, the staff will have to pay
tax on the performance-related payments.
</TEXT>
