<HEADLINE>
FT  26 SEP 92 / London Stock Exchange: Profit-takers move in on share prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND UK STOCK MARKET EDITOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ADVANCE in UK share prices extended over the past week and a half met a
significant check yesterday morning when the stock market re-assessed the
parliamentary speech from Mr John Major, the UK prime minister, as well as
the prospects for the UK economy outside the ERM.
The FT-SE raced ahead by more than 36 points in early trade but turned back
sharply very early in the trading session. Reports that ministerial sources
in Germany had speculated on the possibility of a mini-Europe, excluding
Britain were denied. But the fall in sterling to a low against the D-mark
unsettled a London market conscious of the steadier trend in the French
franc. Also discouraging were signs of political pressures on the UK
government after Thursday's parliamentary debate and the resignation of a
Cabinet member.
By the close of trading in the UK, when Wall Street was showing a fall of 25
Dow points, London stocks were sliding lower. The final reading put the
FT-SE Index at 2,601 exactly, the net fall of 20.2 bringing it to the lowest
level of the day.
The session opened very strongly as the blue chip stocks responded to
strength in stock index futures in late trading on Thursday. Led by the
December contract on the Footsie, the stock market's underlying index moved
up quickly. But when the future contract lost heart, the stock market soon
turned down and attempted rallies in the second half of the session proved
of little avail.
The fear that falling sterling may refuel inflationary pressures was again
reflected in strong gains in index-linked government bonds, which added
around of a point yesterday. Long-dated gilts continued to resist downward
pressure, losing only  1/4 point or so, while the shorts, although a touch
easier, looked for a further cut in base rates soon.
Seaq volume remained high at 693.3m shares, compared with 671.2m on Tuesday.
Stock Exchange statistics disclosed that retail or customer business on
Thursday was worth Pounds 1.4bn.
But, despite the recovery in retail business, the market continues to
resound with complaints that the present quote-driven dealing system on the
London stock market has become impossible to operate profitably and there
are increasing pressures for a change to an order-driven system.
Retail business in equities rose sharply this week as the reduction in UK
base rates to 9 per cent encouraged hopes that rates are headed lower.
</TEXT>
