<HEADLINE>
FT  26 SEP 92 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GLOOMY outlook for the UK economy led to a downbeat session in trading
in stock index futures, writes Joel Kibazo.
The market looked set for a strong day's business when the first trade in
the December contract on the FT-SE was struck at 2,700. This however proved
to be the session's high point - the contract then went into retreat and by
mid-morning was trading some 15 points below its opening level as worries
over the economy surfaced.
Sporadic buying around lunchtime helped bring about a brief rally in
December before the sellers once again gained the upper hand. The poor
performance on Wall Street only served to increase the downward trend in the
contract.
December closed at 2,650, down 33 on its previous close and around 6 points
above its estimated fair value premium to cash of about 40. Turnover was a
reasonable 9,461 lots.
The volume in traded options reached 32,100 contracts. The FT-SE 100 option
traded 10,848 lots. BP was the most active stock option, trading 2,129
contracts, followed by GEC at 2,048.
</TEXT>
