<HEADLINE>
FT  26 SEP 92 / London Stock Exchange: Blow to telecoms stocks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO, STEVE THOMPSON and CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEWS that the UK Department of Trade and Industry (DTI) had granted the
first licence to enable an outsider to compete in the international call
traffic market against such companies as BT and Mercury (the telecoms
division of Cable &amp; Wireless) hit shares of both the big UK telecoms groups.
Cable &amp; Wireless (C &amp; W) shares were particularly unsettled and fell 32, or
5.2 per cent, to 582p, making the stock the third worst performer in the
Footsie. Turnover in C &amp; W was a heavy 5.6m shares. The stock was also
affected by profit-taking after recent outperformance, dealers said.
Analysts said ACC, the US group, had been granted the first 'simple
international resale' licence, covering the UK and Australia, Canada and
Sweden. Analysts said they did not expect any immediate reductions in
earnings forecasts for C &amp; W but that the ACC move would have a greater
impact on C &amp; W than BT because of C &amp; W's higher revenue from its
international business. 'This is confirmation of the real impact of greater
competition in the telecoms business,' said one analyst.
BT shares, hit by recent reductions in earnings and dividend forecasts,
dipped 6 more to 353 1/2 p on 5.7m traded. The decline was cushioned by
optimism generated by the launch of a new marketing initiative - Lifetime -
by its Cellnet cellular phone business.
Market enthusiasm for Lifetime, which offers a lower tariff to cellular
customers, boosted sentiment in Securicor, the minority shareholder in
Cellnet. Securicor 'A' stock rose 5 to 559p. Vodafone, Cellnet's arch rival,
settled 7 higher at 335p, still boosted by a broker's switch recommendation.
Granada wanted
Leisure and media group Granada continued its strong run following recent
meetings with analysts. Yesterday, it was the turn of SG Warburg and Carr
Kitcat and Aitken to recommend the stock; the shares jumped 12 to 258p on
hefty volume of 5.7m.
Sentiment was also improved by news that two directors had made substantial
share purchases this week, prior to Granada going into its closed season.
Chief executive Mr Gerry Robinson spent around Pounds 750,000 on 300,000
shares, while the head of Granada Television, Mr Charles Allen, bought a
further 85,000 for Pounds 200,000.
Mr Jeffrey Harwood at Carr's said that Granada, which has been able to
curtail expenditure on Sky TV and elsewhere in the group, is now 'turning
into a formidable cash generator.'
Enterprise Oil and Lasmo attracted strong support early in the session, much
of it said to have emanated from the US. Enterprise closed 6 higher at 412p,
but Lasmo failed to hold on to an initial gain and settled a net 1 1/2 off
at 164p.
Dreadful quarterly figures from Continental Corporation, one of the big US
insurance groups, were the trigger for a sharp upturn in the UK composite
insurances. A reduced dividend and heavy losses resulting from Hurricane
damage prompted insurance analysts to take the view that US insurance rates
would have to be increased, thereby signalling a significant increase in
international rates.
The prospect of higher premiums, plus the strengthening of the composites'
balance sheets from the big gains in the equity market in recent sessions,
saw share prices race higher.
Commercial Union, with its minimal exposure to domestic mortgage indemnity
losses, ran up 16 to 535p, closely followed by General Accident, 12 firmer
at 521p. Sun Alliance edged up 7 to 310p and Royal Insurance hardend to
185p, the last-named after exceptionally heavy turnover of 5.9m. Insurance
brokers shared in the upsurge led by Willis Corroon which put on 20 to 208p
and Sedgwick, 12 firmer at 145p.
US-led selling in the pharmaceutical sector continued, fuelled on Wall
Street by disappointing data on a drug marketed by Merck. Smithkline
retreated 13 to 481p, Wellcome 13 to 950p and Glaxo 9 to 770p.
Waste management groups suffered as Leigh Interests issued a profits warning
due to a downturn in business. The shares collapsed 51 to 175p.
Several stocks in the transport sector were in demand. Among them, BAA moved
8 ahead to 715p, and P&amp;O improved 3 to 395p. Tiphook gained 8 to 278p.
Shares in tobacco machinery maker Molins jumped 18 to 319p, after the
company reported an improvement in interim profits from Pounds 6.8m to
Pounds 7.2m, and raised the dividend by 50 percent to 4.5p. Investors
favoured Vosper Thorneycroft, and the shares jumped 5 to 394p. Uncertainty
following the early retirement of the chief executive at wire rope maker
Bridon upset the shares and they closed 10 down at 48p.
Following a bear raid on Thursday, Allied Lyons came under renewed pressure
as some trader's decided the brewery group's recent outperformance was
overdone. The shares slumped 27 to 611p. A similar fate befell Whitbread,
the 'A' shares falling 15 to 450p, with UBS Phillips and Drew said to be
particularly negative. Meanwhile, Kleinwort Benson reinforced its buy stance
on Greenalls, the shares climbing 9 to 394p. Food manufacturer Northern
Foods continued a successful round of presentations to brokers. The shares
put on 4 to 283p.
BZW advised clients to take profits in Tate and Lyle, the shares declining
18 to 342p. County NatWest was also targeting Tate's, reportedly advising a
switch into United Biscuits, up 6 to 316p.
Abbey National moved up to 320p early in the session, still boosted by the
BZW buy recommendation, but quickly ran out of steam and fell away to 311p,
a net fall of 6. Barclays attracted fresh and sizeable buying interest,
reflecting the substantial shift in sentiment in the sector since the UK
withdrawal from the ERM and the cut in UK interest rates. Barclays shares
settled 8 higher at 374p on 10m traded. NatWest, on the other hand, slipped
8 to 365p.
SG Warburg, a strong performer at the start of the week when the shares
responded to the big increase in stockmarket activity and also to
speculation of a possible merger involving the bank, eased 2 to 534p.
Kleinwort Benson hardened 3 to 296p.
United Newspapers continued to bask in the glow of its well-recived interim
results on Thursday, with several brokers producing positive notes on the
publishing group. The shares added 5 to 430p. UBS Phillips and Drew, the UK
based securities house, was said to be recommending clients switch into
United out of Pearson, off 11 at 387p.
Solid results from Central Television sent the shares ahead 70 to 1445p.
However, disappointing first half results from HTV knocked the share price
by 14 to 27p.
The aerospace sector was particularly busy. Turnover in British Aerospace,
which reported interim figures below the worst market expectations earlier
this week, reached 6m in strong two-way business. The shares held up
relatively well easing only a penny to 125p.
