<HEADLINE>
FT  26 SEP 92 / UK Company News: Wembley advances to Pounds 2.5m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WEMBLEY, the leisure group, reported a trebled increase in first half
pre-tax profits but a reduced interim dividend as consumers continued to
show a reluctance to spend.
Sir Brian Wolfson, chairman, said last April's optimism about 1992 was based
on the assumption that this year would be no worse than last. However
takings per head and attendances were both down and operating profit margins
fell for the group as a whole.
Pre-tax profits rose from Pounds 709,000 to Pounds 2.5m on sales up 17 per
cent at Pounds 96.8m (Pounds 82.9m) in the six months to June 30. Earnings
per share rose from 0.16p to 0.27p after allowing for the January rights
issue that raised Pounds 37m.
Wembley is not anticipating an early improvement in the economy, despite
recent renewed hopes of lower interest rates. 'The economy will stay flat
this year,' said Sir Brian. 'We are going further than this and assuming
that this (level of economic activity) is the new reality.'
As a result, Wembley is proposing to cut the interim dividend from 0.9p to
0.2p. The shares closed down 4p at 21p.
Asset sales cut gearing to 60 per cent from about 75 per cent after the
rights issue. However, Wembley showed a Pounds 1.4m extraordinary item
mainly relating to goodwill written off on purchase of the Hong Kong night
club which the group has now sold.
Operationally, UK trading improved with margins increasing at the Wembley
Stadium complex following cost cutting.
National Leisure Catering and Keith Prowse tickets had a much stronger first
half. The Ticketing Group joint venture with Expedier Leisure was hit by
lower attendances at West End theatres.
The US had a poorer year because of the translation of dollar earnings into
sterling and a turn down in betting at greyhound tracks.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
