<HEADLINE>
FT  26 SEP 92 / UK Company News: Financial restructuring at Fitch
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRAND TRUST, a company controlled by two French former advertising agency
executives and Sir Terence Conran, founder of the Habitat group and retired
chairman of Storehouse, plans to provide Pounds 2.5m in new capital for
Fitch, the lossmaking design consultant, in return for a 60 per cent equity
stake in the restructured group.
The capital injection is part of a financial reconstruction. Share trading
in Fitch, which ran into problems partly because of high interest costs on
property-related borrowings, was suspended in July at 41p pending the
outcome of talks with its bankers on a refinancing package.
Brand Trust is controlled by Mr Jean-Francois Bentz, former head of design
at Roux, Seguela, Cayzac et Goudard (RSCG), one of the largest French
advertising groups, and Mr Bernard Roux, former RSCG president.
Brand Trust and Sir Terence will pay 11.7p per share for a total of 21.35m
new shares. Brand Trust will have 35 per cent of the enlarged share capital
and Sir Terence 25 per cent. Existing ordinary shareholders will see their
stake diluted from 86.85 per cent to 18.9 per cent, while convertible
preference shareholders, who currently would hold 13.15 per cent of the
equity on conversion, will have their stock converted on enhanced terms into
an 11.1 per cent equity stake.
If Fitch's existing shareholders agree the restructuring at an extraordinary
meeting on October 19, Mr Bentz will become its European chief executive,
and Mr Roux and Sir Terence will join the board as non-executive directors.
As part of the financial reconstruction Fitch's principal banker, National
Westminster, has agreed to restructure its borrowings. The company has also
reached agreement with its landlords and will sell Fitch Benoy, an
architectural practice based in Newark, to its managing director, Mr Fitch
said yesterday.
Separately, Fitch reported increased pre-tax losses of Pounds 1.81m (Pounds
675,000), including Pounds 1.72m (Pounds 752,000) in exceptional charges,
for the six months to June 30. Losses per share were 31.9p (14.2p).
</TEXT>
