<HEADLINE>
FT  26 SEP 92 / UK Company News: Further cost-cutting at HTV as losses
increase to Pounds 5m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HTV GROUP has revealed details of a do-or-die Pounds 10m cost-cutting
programme as the company announced an increased pre-tax loss of Pounds 5.03m
for the six months to June, which was worse than expected.
The share price dropped from 41p to 27p.
Pressure is on the company, which has the independent television licence for
Wales and the west of England, because from the beginning of next year it
will start paying Pounds 20.5m a year plus 2 per cent of its advertising
revenue to the Treasury under broadcasting legislation.
The programme will include a year-long pay freeze for all staff, a reduction
in the actuarial costs of 'luxurious' pensions and an end to special loyalty
bonuses. A restructuring bringing together the separate Wales and west
divisions is already under way.
The company is not declaring an interim dividend and the question of a final
dividend will be reviewed in the light of autumn trading. Losses per share
were 5.4p (5.2p).
Mr Louis Sherwood, chairman, conceded that the independence of the company
was at stake unless the savings were made. 'We are fiercely independent and
we are going to do out best to remain independent.'
He added that the company would continue to reduce expenditure next year
'consistent with our licence obligations, in order to deliver to our
shareholders a return to profits and dividends'.
What Mr Sherwood described as 'extremely disappointing results' were mainly
the result of a sharp and unexpected decline in share of HTV's share of ITV
advertising revenue from 6.2 per cent to 5.8 per cent.
There had been an improvement in operating losses to Pounds 2.09m (Pounds
2.69m) on lower turnover of Pounds 65.1m (Pounds 80.7m). Net interest
charges were lower at Pounds 1.89m (Pounds 2.16m) but there was an
exceptional charge of Pounds 1m covering restructuring and redundancy costs.
Last year's interim pre-tax loss was Pounds 4.84m.
Mr Chris Rowlands, recently appointed group finance director, said that
almost all the Pounds 10m planned savings had been identified.
Until recently HTV believed that the UK economy would improve after the
general election. Now no end to the recession was in sight.
'It now seems to us prudent to plan on the assumption that these conditions
will continue for an indefinite period,' Mr Sherwood said.
The scale of the potential problem is shown by a review of advertising
revenue commissioned from consultants Booz Allen. In its franchise bid HTV
assumed 3.3 per cent growth in real annual advertising revenue throughout
the 10 years of the franchise. Booz Allen has told HTV the growth is likely
to be less than 2 per cent.
</TEXT>
