FT  26 SEP 92 / Letter: Taxing, but intellectual too
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr S MITHA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Your article, 'Students say no to taxing careers with the Revenue'
(September 22), highlighted the alleged unpopularity of the Tax Inspectorate
as a graduate career. The reality is a little different.
In 1992 alone we have received over 5,500 applications from honours
graduates for just 30 vacancies.
These applicants have realised that a career in the Tax Inspectorate offers
what most graduates actually want: good training and career development,
intellectual challenge, and progression on merit. All this in a dynamic
culture.
S Mitha,
assistant director
(recruitment),
Inland Revenue,
